author: AccessWDUN Staff
title: Moon shines again at meet in Tennessee
text:
Monday October 19th, 2015 10:52PM 9:59PM ( 53 minutes ago ) News Alert Posted 8:12PM on Monday 19th October 2015 ( 2 hours ago ) Moon shines again at meet in Tennessee Tim "T" Moon preps for a lift. Related Articles Moon rides roller-coaster weekend at Vegas meets Local powerlifter Moon continues to excel, presses almost 794 pounds to nab title Area competitor House finishes in top 10 at USA Powerlifting Championships Team USA dominates GPA World Championships in Athens 
LEBANON, Tenn. — Lifting at the Elite Powerlifting Federation's "Bash for Cash" meet in Lebanon, Tenn., area lifter Tim "T" Moon, once again, impressed. 
The 286-pound Moon put up the heaviest bench press of the day in the equipped master's class with an astounding 805-pound lift to shatter the EPF world record and take home the top prize of $1,000. The performance came soon after taking world titles in two other associations, including an all-time world record for benchpressers over the age of 50 with a lift of over 821 pounds in the World United Amateur Powerlifting World Championships in East Peoria, Ill., cementing his claim to the best equipped 50-plus-year-old bench press specialist in history. He also came close on a lift of 835 at the EPF competition. 
"Five days of competition in four weeks. I guess that's kinda unusual?" Moon asked with a smile, already knowing that is almost unheard of. 
The 51-year-old Moon is a Gainesville area resident and a 1982 alumnus of Jefferson High. 
Also, at the EPF meet, Dahlonega's Eric Head benched 410 pounds in the 148-pound, raw class to take second place by formula. Associated Tags : Tim Moon, Weightlifting © Copyright 2015 AccessWDUN.com
